# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1923-new-york-yankees-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1902 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 83 wins and 53 losses.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1902, the Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Athletics' second baseman Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie had played for the Athletics in 1901, and appeared in just one game in 1902 before the injunction went into effect.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Bronchos, who were subsequently known as the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Following the A's pennant winning season, the *Philadelphia Inquirer* organized a championship parade for the team through the city on Monday night, September 30, 1902.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team proceeded in open carriages and were reviewed by Philadelphia Mayor Ashbridge in front of the *Inquirer'*s building on Market Street.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] "There were more than 25,000 base ball enthusiasts from Philadelphia and nearly every town within a radius of twenty miles of the city in the parade.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] A thousand effigies of the "white elephant" were carried by the paraders.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] There were fifteen bands and twenty fife and drum corps in line to furnish music for the marchers." It was estimated that more than 200,000 turned out for the parade.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The **1903 major league baseball season** began on April 16, 1903.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the Pittsburgh Pirates and the Boston Americans as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first modern World Series on October 1 and ended with Game 8 on October 13.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Americans defeated the Pirates, five games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the World Series, following the one-off 1900 *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] It was also the first inter-league series since the 1890 World's Championship Series between the National League and defunct-since-1891 American Association.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 World Series would also mark the first championship series that is still celebrated today, as all previous series are considered pre-modern and these early contests are discussed by MLB and baseball historians separately.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] However, the 1903 arrangement was primarily between the two participating clubs rather than a formal arrangement between the leagues, essentially making this season's World Series a voluntary event.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The defunct Baltimore Orioles were replaced by a new franchise in New York City known as the New York Highlanders; it was the last change to the lineup of AL and NL franchises until 1953.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would not return to Baltimore until the St.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns relocated there as a new Baltimore Orioles in 1954.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Orphans and Cleveland Bronchos were renamed as the Chicago Cubs and Cleveland Naps, respectively.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1901 season.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the last season with this format, as the following season would see an increase of games played.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 16 with four teams playing, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 20, with a doubleheader between the Philadelphia Athletics and the Boston Americans.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 27, while the American League would see its final day of the season on September 29.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The inaugural World Series took place between October 1 and October 13.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (6 in AL, 9 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Americans defeating the Pittsburgh Pirates in the 1903 World Series in eight games.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Termed the "Battle of Ohio", the Cincinnati Reds and Cleveland Naps played an unofficial best of 11-game exhibition series after the regular season, with Cleveland winning the series six games to three.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 season saw the enfranchisement of the New York Highlanders, in place of the folded Baltimore Orioles, playing at Hilltop Park in New York City, New York, where they would play for ten seasons through 1912.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] On August 8, in what is known as the worst disaster in American sports spectating history, Black Saturday, a section of balcony at the Philadelphia Phillies' home at the Baker Bowl collapsed, killing 12 spectators and injuring 232.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Phillies played the last 16 of their 61 home games at the home of the American League crosstown Philadelphia Athletics, Columbia Park from August 20.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The New York Highlanders' 1903 season was the team's first.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The team was founded as a replacement in the American League for the defunct Baltimore Orioles, was managed by Clark Griffith and played its home games at Hilltop Park (formally "American League Park").
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The club was at first officially the "Greater New York" baseball club, in deference to the established New York Giants, which were based in the Polo Grounds.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] This was the first season for the franchise that would be later known as the now-storied New York Yankees.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] They finished in 4th place in the AL with a record of 72–62.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] "Highlanders" was also originally short for "Gordon's Highlanders", a play on the name of the team President during 1903–1906, Joseph Gordon, along with the noted British military unit called The Gordon Highlanders.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The club was also derisively called "Invaders" in 1903, presumably by writers favorable to the Giants.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The New York press was creative with analogous nicknames for teams.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] In addition to "Highlanders", the team would soon acquire the alternate nickname "Yankees", the name that would soon become official and more famous among baseball fans in the coming decades.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] That word is a synonym for "American" in general, and short for American Leaguers or "Americans" in this case.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] Given the media's penchant for citing popular culture, that nickname was also possibly influenced by the then-current and hugely popular America-centric George M.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] Cohan Broadway play, "Little Johnny Jones", and its centerpiece song, "Yankee Doodle Dandy".
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] New York writers had similarly coined both the established nickname Brooklyn "[Trolley] Dodgers" and the nickname "Superbas" that the denizens of Flatbush carried for a while.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] As with the Highlanders, the latter was based on something unrelated, namely a circus act called "Hanlon's Superbas"; the Dodgers were managed by Ned Hanlon at that time.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The **1904 Boston Americans season** was the fourth season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 95 wins and 59 losses, 1+1⁄2 games ahead of the New York Highlanders.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The Americans were set to play the National League (NL) champion New York Giants in the 1904 World Series; however, the Giants refused to play.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 7 home runs and had 84 RBIs, and Freddy Parent with a .291 batting average.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 43 appearances (41 starts) and pitched 40 complete games with a 26–16 record and 1.97 ERA, while striking out 200 in 380 innings.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (23–14) and Jesse Tannehill (21–11).
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; September 13 at Philadelphia, September 14 vs.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-boston-americans-season] Both ties against New York were the second games of doubleheaders.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-boston-americans-season] Note: Stats in brackets are derived from Retrosheet which differ from the stats found on MLB.com.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] The 1904 New York Highlanders season, the team's second, finished with the team in second place in the American League with a record of 92–59.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] The team was managed by Clark Griffith and played home games at Hilltop Park.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] The casual use of that nickname suggests it was already in the popular lexicon, although "Highlanders" would continue to be the primary (and equally unofficial) nickname for several more years.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] The Highlanders were in the thick of the American League pennant race throughout the season, leading by two games as late as September 20.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] This led to the New York Giants announcement that they would not play in the World Series, since they considered the Highlanders to be only a "minor league" team.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] On the final day of the season at Hilltop Park, New York pitcher Jack Chesbro threw a wild pitch in the ninth inning, giving the Boston Americans the win, and the 1904 AL pennant.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] Even though it was Boston who stole the pennant on the final day, the Giants stuck to their word and their refusal prevented the World Series from being played.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1904-new-york-highlanders-season] It would be a century later, in 2004, the next time Boston directly eliminated the Yankees from title contention, when they did so in the final game of the 2004 ALCS, a hundred years later in a repeat of sorts of the events of that year, the beginning of a long rivalry between the two clubs.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1923-new-york-yankees-season] The 1923 New York Yankees season was the 21st season for the American League franchise.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1923-new-york-yankees-season] Manager Miller Huggins led the team to their third straight pennant with a 98–54 record, 16 games ahead of the second place Detroit Tigers.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1923-new-york-yankees-season] The Yankees moved into the now-famous Yankee Stadium.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1923-new-york-yankees-season] In the 1923 World Series, they avenged their 1921 and 1922 losses by defeating the New York Giants in 6 games, 4 games to 2, and won their first World Series title.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1923-new-york-yankees-season] The Yankees began their first World Championship Season on April 18 as they opened Yankee Stadium.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1923-new-york-yankees-season] Babe Ruth christened the new stadium with a home run in the Yankees' 4–1 victory over the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1923-new-york-yankees-season] The stadium would later be called "the House that Ruth Built".
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1923-new-york-yankees-season] On May 5, the Yankees beat the Philadelphia Athletics 7–2 at Yankee Stadium to regain first place, the Yankees would never fall back in the standings for the rest of the season.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1923-new-york-yankees-season] Babe Ruth set a Yankees record for highest batting average in one season by hitting .393.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1923-new-york-yankees-season] Ruth also finished the season with 41 home runs and 131 RBIs.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1923-new-york-yankees-season] Ruth's average was not enough to win the batting title, as Ruth finished in second place to Detroit's Harry Heilmann who batted .403.
[src:1923-new-york-yankees-season/1923-new-york-yankees-season] Ruth reached base safely 379 times during the season.
